Study on Sexual Dimorphism in Anthros Part 2 - Hyenas
After the success of my paper on the "doeboi" phenomenon amongst male deer, I was granted funding to examine hyenas. As we both know hyenas have not integrated well with human society, with many still living in the wild and fighting against human colonization. For this study, we questioned 50 civilized males and 50 females, and we thank their owners graciously for providing us these subjects. We also observed hyenas in the wild for anecdotal information, but were unable to make data on these subjects.
Sexual dimorphism is common in all species, with genders differing in physiology ranging from changes in hair or fur, to new or different limbs entirely. Hyenas present the usual dimorphism present in most mammals, however it is flipped. The females are taller and stronger than males - the average height for a male is 5', but for females it is 6'. Muscle density and placement is different, with females having around twice the muscles per-pound as their male counterparts, especially around the shoulders and arms. In our tests, females could lift twice the weight of males on average.
Personality traits like aggression and boldness also differ, and is why hyenas are matriarchal in the wild. We conducted a simple test; a small sugary treat with a note saying it belonged to someone else left unattended in a room with them for 5 minutes, with no observers. 41 of the 50 females took the food, often within the first minute. Of the males only 8 took it. Interviewing the males afterwards, the most common reason for leaving the treat was fear of punishment or repercussion. Interviewed females gave a lot of reasons for taking it, with sentiments that they could "take" the punishment or intimidate their way out of it. This matches observations of wild hyenas, where the females will often harass or bully males for food or other perks.
Pictured: a female and male hyena subject, mother and son. (https://desu-usergeneratedcontent.xyz/trash/image/1650/03/1650036456698.jpg)
This abrasive personality extends to how well trained they are. All male subjects were comfortable with their collar and leash, and performed simple orders such as walking at a humans heel, sitting unattended and staying quiet with ease. Female subjects varied greatly, for every well trained female two would give a fuss, anywhere from resistance to attempting to attack their handler. It should be noted that of the obedient females, each was owned or traned by a tamer specializing in unruly species such as hyena.
On to the part that gets the most humans confused - the genitalia of female hyenas. While most females have a rather normal mammalian vagina, some instead have an unusual organ, with many unfamiliar human tamers and hunters believing it to be a penis, and calling such females "shemales". This organ is called a pseudopenis, and as the name suggests, it looks like a penis but is not. It is essentially an extended urethra and vaginal canal that is supported by erectile tissue. Like a vagina it gets wet while aroused and is penetrated for mating, and is what the subject gives birth from. Like a penis, it gets erect while aroused and has a "sack" of loose skin underneath, a sort of a faux scrotum they use for scent marking. We believe the gene for this phenomena is recessive - of our 50 participants, only 12 had been born with a pseudopenis, with 2 of those subjects having had corrective surgery per their owners requests. Of our subjects, the average pseudopenis length was 9 inches - for reference, the average males penis was 5.
Pictured: male subject from the study. Subject had no issue with the uniform assigned to him by his owner. (https://desu-usergeneratedcontent.xyz/trash/image/1574/30/1574308515389.jpg)
It is interesting to see the differences between the standard female and those with a pseudopenis (from now on these subjects will be referred to as, "female+"). After noticing female+ subjects appeared to be taller and stronger than female subjects, I decided to rerun my gamut of tests, this time separating female and female+ subjects as separate genders, for the purpose of these tests the subjects that had corrective surgery are considered female+. Females were on average 5'8" - female+ were typically 6'2", they also beat females in muscle density and maximum weight lifted across the board. On to the treat test - only one of the female subjects took the treat, yet 7 female+ took the treat. 4 females struggled or resisted the simple leash tasks, every female+ subjects gave difficulty. It should also be noted - the term "shemale" used earlier is not something any female+ subject wished to be called, many getting offended and rowdy at the term. They simply prefer to be called "female".
Conclusion:
The physical sexual traits of hyenas are, to put it simply, flipped from that of humans and other anthros. The males are weak and meek, the females are strong and assertive. The interesting part to me is the females with a pseudopenis, "female+". There is clear dimorphism between the two groups, despite both being ostensibly female, both capable of being inseminated and giving birth. I believe this species requires more study to fully understand the difference physiology between the two, and this possible third gender.
--Dr. Vaninetti, Professor of Anthro Studies, University of Hamburg
Pictured: female+ subject. Note the larger hands and feet, the muscular arms and legs, and broader shoulders as compared to female subject. (https://desu-usergeneratedcontent.xyz/trash/image/1603/06/1603068516424.jpg)

