The arctic would be easier in certain regards, and more difficult in certain regards.
First and foremost, easier since there's a lot more draw in the resources we have to offer. Ample food and warmth to a bunch of anthros that have to be built to get fat to stay warm, where missing one meal too many can mean certain death, where the climate is as hostile as any predators can be...
Harder because at least in my mind, compared to Africa, it's going to take a good deal longer since you're dealing with loners. Lots of tiny families, tiny communities, no huge cities or microcosms of society/the world/whatever. If the anthros are more like wild animals, no huge herds with very little exception. If they're anything like the Eskimo people and band together, again, smaller communities, plenty of depression and substance abuse problems cause the barren cold is a hellscape. You'll encounter resistance from the traditional folk either not wanting to turn the arctic into some tropical paradise (not that I think humanity would want to do that anyway) or those that really value their culture, their ancestors, and the sheer perseverance it took and still takes to survive up there.
>What are the anthro tribes there like?
Not really tribes at all, smatterings of groups less than 10 people large.
>How do you defeat them?
Offer warmth, food, companionship... Find the best ways to counter the isolation and deprivation up there, and build a really tight-knit community. Maybe have a group of humans wander in "accidentally" and seek refuge and help from the anthros to reclaim their ship/habitat/whatever with the promise of sharing the bounty once the long trek is finished. Go full dances with wolves and join the locals, but make their lives, their families, and their small communities better and stronger. Technology would make hunting easier, and having some extra bodies wouldn't hurt either.
>And what are their women like?
Their women are thicc, nomadic, lone wolf-types for the most part. Calling them paranoid or skittish is just a toe over the line, but they know that the snow is an unforgiving battlefield where only death awaits. Nothing but vast stretches of white snow in every direction, near-invisible predators, scarce food... It'd be enough to drive even the strongest of minds mad.
The men and women that manage to survive there are fighting for their lives on a regular basis, or trying NOT to fight by hiding out and conserving their precious energy and fat reserves.
In my mind, the anthros that can live in the water below the ice might have it the easiest since they have more room to stretch their legs (in the metaphorical sense). Finding stable ice and a place to rest after swimming in freezing-cold water (even with evolution preparing them for it) is dangerous as all hell. The polar bear anthros might have it the roughest since they need to find someplace stable to hibernate and wait out the worst of the cold weather. ...Better to sleep and conserve than fight mother nature, the bloodthirsty bitch that she is.
Of the anthros that CAN form colonies, properly joining and being absorbed into and accepted by the "herd" would be the fun/risky part. Joining a group of seals - eager to help out someone that they'd think was struggling without enough fat or food to brave the cold - would be a wonderfully supportive kind of life, but still brutal. Finding that seal-waifu that's terrified for you and wants to feed you to keep you safe and warm would melt even the coldest of hearts, and starting a family - contributing to the collective - would be a life-changingly joyous event.
Good luck being able to live in or super-near the water, though. Even with advanced technology, it'd be rough...
Anything with a coat to match the snow would pose a challenge. Either you're dealing with prey species that are super skittish and rely on their camouflage and there being enough snow on the ground to blend into, or you turn around to see death given flesh. As their silhouettes blend into everything around them, you start to think your mind's playing tricks on you before you spot the dozen or so pairs of eyes wondering if you're dinner or something that isn't worth messing with.
Wolves would probably be the easiest anthros to get along with. Dig up the history books and offer them food and warmth, and start the domestication process all over again. Before you know it, you've got stealth waifus dragging your sleeping bag to safer ground, only you don't know it because everything looks exactly the same when you finally wake up.
If taking the more aboriginal approach, igloos would be a must. Either we, the humans, introduce the anthros to it, or we simply help them improve what they've already got with high-tech snow-cutting tools. Cozy up to your anthro of choice in the close quarters of an igloo and warm the place up the old fashioned way in between sharing your nutrient rich food with her.
Big momma of a polar bear, thicc but sluggish on land whale/seal/walrus girl, or a whole pack of "smaller" anthros that sleep in piles to conserve warmth. The arctic would be a hell of a place to try and conquer, but it'd be cozy as all hell under the right circumstances.

